Introduction

For my capstone project, I have chosen to generate a heatmap of my re-analyzed data. I am comparing RNAseq data from my rs356182-lesion clones to several wildtype controls (both differentiated and undifferentiated). Previously, I was using results generated by Steve Pierce to generate figures and do comparisons, but we decided some of the samples didnt make sense to include anymore. I chose to re-perform the analysis from scratch using only the relevant fastq sample files. Samples needed to be unpacked, have the adapters trimmed off, be aligned to a reference genome, and output a reads/gene count file. This was done in several steps below. The presence of both single end and paired-end data made the analysis more complicated.

Processing data on the HPC

The Genomics core provided us with fastq files from our RNAseq experiments. For this analysis, I am pulling from three different experiments (Single-end read LUHMES differentiated vs undifferentiated, paired-end read LUHMES differentiated vs undifferentiated, and my lesion clones). The fastq files were collected into one directory in my folder on the server.For the sake of brevity, I have removed all of the extra stuff I would normally include in code to echo job details Or provide simple instructions for myself. First I index the reference genome. I included the code for retrieving the genome if necessary.

Thresholding my count data

Now I have all of my count data with gene info in one object; my_dge. I am going to plot my raw counts against their cpm data to determine what the threshold for low counts should be. In general, a threshold should be chosen for a CPM corresponding to about 10 reads. In the example (https://combine-australia.github.io/RNAseq-R/06-rnaseq-day1.html), they use 0.5 cpm. For my data it looks like that will be closer to 0.115.

myCPM <-cpm(my_dge) #Create an object transformed for counts per million

plot(myCPM[,1],my_dge$counts[,1],ylim=c(0,20),xlim=c(0,0.25))  
abline(h=10, v=0.115, col="red")

thresh <- myCPM > 0.115 # Apply my newly determined threshold to my cpm data
table(rowSums(thresh))

Principle component analysis

plotMDS(my_dge) # This is a simple plot that provides a lot of info based on principle component analysis

MDS plots provides a simple visualization of the principle components accounting for variability between samples. In order to get a better idea of what makes our components different, I use a PCA plot grouped by different parameters of our data. To accomplish this in a higher throughput manner, I wrote my first simple function.

#For a better look at principle components, I will use a PCA plot. I'm also adding in a bunch of extra factors to see how they stratify across PCs.
pca_data <- prcomp(t(logcounts), scale = T)

pData <- data.frame(pca_data$x)

pData$Geno <- c("A/-","A/-","A/-","G/-","G/-","G/-","A/G","A/G","A/G", rep("LD", times=9), rep("UD", times=9))
pData$ends <- c(rep("paired",times=10), "single", "paired", "single", "paired", rep("single", times=4), "paired", "single", "paired", "single", "paired", rep("single", times=4))
pData$crispr <- c(rep("exposed", times=9), rep("naive", times=18))
pData$edited <- c(rep("TRUE", times=6), rep("FALSE", times=21))
pData$investigator <- c(rep("JP", times=9), rep("TT", times=18))
pData$diff <- c(rep("diff", times=18), rep("undiff", times=9))

#write.csv2(data.frame(pData), './PCA_dataframe.csv')

var_explained <- pca_data$sdev^2/sum(pca_data$sdev^2) # Add variance to plot axis

Writing a figure-function

As is evident from the above code chunk, I was attempting to automate the figure making process to some degree. This way, my figures would be more uniform and generating them would be faster. The chunk was set up so you can change 3 variable strings in a vector at the top of the chunk, and the code would reference those variables to generate figures with those parameters. It wasnt until after I made functional versions of these caveman functions that I learned how to do this properly using the function method. Now when I want to change parameters, rather than pasting the entire chunk again, its just one line that, making my output much more concise.

pca.fig <- function(data, x_pc, y_pc, grp) {
  vvar1 <- as.numeric(substring(x_pc,3,3))
  vvar2 <- as.numeric(substring(y_pc,3,3))
  ggplot(data=data, aes_string(x=paste0(x_pc), y=paste0(y_pc))) +
    geom_point(aes(color = grp),size=3) +
    theme_minimal() +
    ggtitle("PCA of RNAseq Data") +
    xlab(paste0(x_pc, ": ", round(var_explained[vvar1]*100,1),"% variance explained")) + 
    ylab(paste0(y_pc, ": ", round(var_explained[vvar2]*100,1),"% variance explained")) +
    geom_convexhull(alpha = 0.4,aes(fill = grp))
}

a <- pca.fig(pData, 'PC1','PC2', pData$Geno)
b <- pca.fig(pData, 'PC3', "PC4", pData$Geno)
c <- pca.fig(pData, 'PC5', "PC6", pData$Geno)
d <- pca.fig(pData, 'PC7', "PC8", pData$Geno)

# New code generates 4 figures in 15 lines total. The old code would've taken about 80 lines to do the same

plot_grid(a, b,c,d, labels = "AUTO", nrow = 2, ncol = 2)

Heatmap

Now we have everything we need to generate a simple heatmap. Initially I will use this simple package to generate a heatmap of the 500 most variable genes. The problem here is that the most variable genes by far are differentially expressed between the differentiated versus undifferentiated samples, so we need to exclude undifferentiaed samples if we want to get a better idea of what makes my lesion-clones unique.

var_genes <- apply(logcounts, 1, var) # Store the variance of each gene in the object var_gene

select_var <- names(sort(var_genes, decreasing=TRUE))[1:500] # Grab only the 500 most variable genes. Could be any number
highly_variable_lcpm <- logcounts[select_var,] # Filter the data for those 500 genes

# Pull in a color palette
mypalette <- brewer.pal(11,"RdYlBu")

# Plot the heatmap
heatmap.2(highly_variable_lcpm,col=rev(morecols(50)),trace="none", main="Top 500 most variable genes across samples",scale="row")

Z-score

Now that I have my data in counts per million, we normalize the genes using a z-score calculation. This calculation takes the observed value, subtracts the average value for each gene, and then divides by the standard deviation per gene to give you a value of deviance from the norm.I am confident that theres a much easier way to do this, but this is how I did it.

zdata <- expr_data   ### Don't work on the primary data set
zdata$avg <- rowMeans(expr_data[,3:29]) ### Add a column for row averages
zdata$sd <- apply(expr_data[,3:29],1,sd) ### Add a column for row standard deviations
zdata1 <- cbind(zdata[,1:2], ((zdata[,3:29]-zdata[,30])/zdata[,31])) ### Make a new data frame with the gene ID/symbol and Z-scores (observed - average / sd). 

### FOR T-TEST P-VALUES
# First, create the function to do t-tests between groups and pull out the p-value
ttestdata <-function(zdata1, grp1, grp2) {
  x= zdata1[grp1]
  y= zdata1[grp2]
  x= as.numeric(x)
  y= as.numeric(y)
  results= t.test(x,y)
  results$p.value
}

# apply the function pairwise between each group. Later we will do this same thing but for Fold-change
pval_A_vs_G   <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(3:5),   grp2= c(6:8)))
pval_AG_vs_A  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(9:11),  grp2= c(3:5)))
pval_A_vs_LD  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(3:5),   grp2= c(12:21)))
pval_A_vs_UD  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(3:5),   grp2= c(22:29)))
pval_AG_vs_G  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(9:11),  grp2= c(6:8)))
pval_G_vs_LD  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(6:8),   grp2= c(12:21)))
pval_G_vs_UD  <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(6:8),   grp2= c(22:29)))
pval_AG_vs_LD <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(9:11),  grp2= c(12:21)))
pval_AG_vs_UD <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(9:11),  grp2= c(22:29)))
pval_LD_vs_UD <- (apply(zdata1,1,ttestdata, grp1 = c(12:21), grp2= c(22:29)))

###### FOR FOLD-CHANGE ANALYSIS
# Find mean for each group
A_ = apply(zdata1[,3:5],1,mean)
G_ = apply(zdata1[,6:8],1,mean)
AG = apply(zdata1[,9:11],1,mean)
LD = apply(zdata1[,12:21],1,mean)
UD = apply(zdata1[,22:29],1,mean)

#Since we've already log transformed our data, we can find fold-change by taking the difference between groups
logFC_A_vs_G   <- (A_ - G_) 
logFC_AG_vs_A  <- (AG - A_)
logFC_A_vs_LD  <- (A_ - LD)
logFC_A_vs_UD  <- (A_ - UD)
logFC_AG_vs_G  <- (AG - G_)
logFC_G_vs_LD  <- (G_ - LD)
logFC_G_vs_UD  <- (A_ - UD)
logFC_AG_vs_LD <- (AG - LD)
logFC_AG_vs_UD <- (AG - UD)
logFC_LD_vs_UD <- (LD - UD)


### Now bind all of our data into one big table
compData <- cbind(zdata1, pval_A_vs_G, logFC_A_vs_G, pval_A_vs_LD, logFC_A_vs_LD, pval_A_vs_UD, logFC_A_vs_UD, pval_AG_vs_A, logFC_AG_vs_A, pval_AG_vs_G, logFC_AG_vs_G, pval_AG_vs_LD, logFC_AG_vs_LD, pval_AG_vs_UD, logFC_AG_vs_UD, pval_G_vs_LD, logFC_G_vs_LD, pval_G_vs_UD, logFC_G_vs_UD, pval_LD_vs_UD, logFC_LD_vs_UD)

write.csv(data.frame(compData), './20210421_comparison_data.csv') ### Save here as a checkpoint

Volcano plots

I use volcano plots to display differentially expressed genes between groups. I found a package to make enhanced volcano plots so I tested it out with the A/- versus G/- comparison below.

EnhancedVolcano(compData, 
                lab= compData$Symbol, 
                x= 'logFC_A_vs_G', 
                y= 'pval_A_vs_G',
                pCutoff = 0.01,
                FCcutoff = 1,
                selectLab = c("SNCA", "LRRK2", "NEUROG2", "PRKD2", "LINC02003"),
                colAlpha = 0.5,
                ylim = c(0,5),
                xlim = c(-3.5,3.5),
                legendPosition = "right",
                legendLabSize = 12,
                #colGradient = c('red','royalBlue'),
                drawConnectors = T,
                widthConnectors = 1,
                boxedLabels = F,
                subtitle = "A/- versus G/- clones",
                title = "Differential expression",
                caption = bquote(~Log[2]~ "fold change cutoff, 1; p-value cutoff, 0.01"),
                )
